Plan:
{{.Plan}}

- Make the code changes. For compiler changes, update both the implementation and
  any affected LLVM IR patterns. For Promise/stdlib changes, run `bin/build` to
  re-embed updated modules (NEVER run `go build` directly — it produces a broken
  binary).
- NEVER work around a compiler/language bug or test-infra issue — if you hit a
  limitation, resolve it inline or file it with mcp__tracker__create and stop.
- Single source of truth — no duplicated state or logic. Keep each piece of state in
  ONE place; never maintain two copies that must be kept in sync. If you genuinely
  need a duplicate for performance, make it an explicit cache (one clear owner,
  defined invalidation), not a second source of truth. Implement each behavior ONCE
  and reuse it — do not copy an implementation and add minor variations. Always strive
  for the simplest single implementation source.
- Watch for silent systemic bugs in code you touch: MEMORY LEAKS (zero tolerance —
  the repo has 0 leaks and 0 `allow_leaks` tags; every droppable/heap-allocating
  type needs a drop path), double free, use after free, missing scope cleanup,
  concurrency races (lock ordering, park/wake, channel close), and resource waste.
  File any at critical priority.
- Write tests for every behavioral change — cover the fix, edge cases, and error
  paths, not just the happy path. Go: `generateIR`+`assertContains` (codegen),
  `checkErrs`+`expectError` (sema), `ownerOK`/`ownerErrs` (ownership). Promise:
  STRONGLY prefer batch tests (`test` annotation + `assert()`) — every batch test
  across all files compiles into ONE binary, so they scale to the ~6000-test suite.
  A snapshot test (`main()` + `test(expected: "...")`) compiles a SEPARATE binary
  PER test, which does not scale — use it ONLY when exact stdout genuinely matters.
  Co-locate `*_test.pr` with the source for module changes; reserve `tests/` for
  genuinely cross-cutting e2e cases.
- Run `{{.VerifyCmd}}` and ensure it passes (it can take many minutes — wait for
  it). The output must show 0 leaks; any leak is a regression you must fix. NEVER add
  `allow_leaks: true`.
- {{.DeferCommit}} Concretely: do NOT run `git commit`/`git push`, and do NOT
  invoke the `/commit`, `/do`, `/push`, or `/review` skills — they commit/push and
  would pre-empt the flow's own land step. Leave every change uncommitted in the
  worktree.
- You do NOT need to write the resolution summary either:
  a dedicated step produces it after the work is merged.

